</sup></summary><div class=3D"ptx-footnote__contents" id=3D"eg_ITmaxwell-1-=
1">To be picky, these are Maxwell=E2=80=99s equations in the absence of a m=
aterial medium and in Gaussian units.</div></details> <details class=3D"ptx=
-footnote" aria-live=3D"polite" id=3D"eg_ITmaxwell-1-2"><summary class=3D"p=
tx-footnote__number" title=3D"Footnote 4.1.4"><sup>=E2=80=894=E2=80=89</sup=
></summary><div class=3D"ptx-footnote__contents" id=3D"eg_ITmaxwell-1-2">On=
e important consequence of Maxwell=E2=80=99s equations is that electromagne=
tic radiation, like light, propagate at the speed of light.</div></details>=
 <details class=3D"ptx-footnote" aria-live=3D"polite" id=3D"eg_ITmaxwell-1-=
3"><summary class=3D"ptx-footnote__number" title=3D"Footnote 4.1.5"><sup>=
=E2=80=895=E2=80=89</sup></summary><div class=3D"ptx-footnote__contents" id=
=3D"eg_ITmaxwell-1-3">James Clerk Maxwell (1831=E2=80=931879) was a Scottis=
h mathematical physicist. In a poll of prominent physicists, Maxwell was vo=
ted the third greatest physicist of all time. Only Newton and Einstein beat=
 him.</div></details>, which form the foundation of classical electromagnet=
ism.</div>
